4 HJR___ SUPPORTING THE CREATION OF A BICAMERAL HISTORICALLY
5 BLACK COLLEGES AND UNIVERSITIES (HBCUs) LEGISLATIVE CAUCUS.
6
7 WHEREAS, Alabama is home to 14 Historically Black
8 Colleges and Universities (HBCUs), including six private and
9 eight public HBCUs; the highest number for a state in the
10 country; and
11 WHEREAS, originally founded as early as 1867 and as
12 recently as 1975, the private HBCUs include Miles College,
13 Oakwood University, Selma University, Stillman College,
14 Talladega College, and Tuskegee University, and the public
15 HBCUs include Alabama State University, Alabama A&M
16 University, Bishop State Community College, Gadsden State
17 Community College, H. Councill Trenholm State Community
18 College, J.F. Drake State Community and Technical College,
19 Lawson State Community College, and Shelton State Community
20 College; and
21 WHEREAS, HBCUs have expanded access to higher
22 education for students who historically faced barriers;
23 these institutions have played an important role in
24 producing leaders in education, business, government, health
25 care, and science; HBCUs also preserve important cultural
26 traditions and provide supportive environments that help
27 students succeed academically and professionally; and
28 WHEREAS, nationally, HBCUs generate $16.9 billion
Page 1

WHEREAS, nationally, HBCUs generate $16.9 billion
HJR47 INTRODUCED
29 dollars annually in economic impact, grant over 20 percent
30 of undergraduate degrees for Black Americans, and generate
31 134,000 jobs nationwide; and
32 WHEREAS, it is imperative that a high-quality
33 education is inclusive and promoted and provided for all
34 students attending institutions of higher education in this
35 state, with particular attention being focused on our HBCUs;
36 now therefore,
37 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, BOTH
38 HOUSES THEREOF CONCURRING, That this body supports the
39 creation of a bicameral legislative caucus, to be named the
40 Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUs)
41 Legislative Caucus, to protect, promote, and support the
42 interests of HBCUs and students receiving educational
43 instruction through HBCUs in this state.
44 (a) The guiding principles for state HBCU caucuses
45 include:
46 (1) Advocating for fair funding and strong support
47 services;
48 (2) Partnering with institutions, communities, and
49 industries to create new opportunities;
50 (3) Informing lawmakers about challenges and
51 solutions for HBCUs; and
52 (4)Promoting the value of HBCUs to the state's
53 economy and future workforce.
54 (b) The founding members of the legislative caucus
55 shall include any member of the Alabama Senate and Alabama
56 House of Representatives who is interested in the provision
Page 2

House of Representatives who is interested in the provision
HJR47 INTRODUCED
57 of consistent, available high-quality education throughout
58 Alabama's institutions of higher education, including HBCUs.
59 (c) Upon passage of this resolution and the filing of
60 a bicameral Legislative Caucus Certificate of Registration
61 with the Secretary of State, the Lieutenant Governor shall
62 call the first meeting of the caucus, at which time the
63 members shall elect a chair and a vice chair from among the
64 membership. The caucus may then meet as necessary to conduct
65 business.
